    "content": "Another city might reject Flock Cameras\n\n- An audit on CMPD’s use of automated license plate reader camera data, sought in April, has not been produced. (the audit is long overdue)\n- Concerned about footage being shared with federal agencies, including ICE, residents and immigrant advocates urge: “Get the Flock Out of @Costa Mesa.”\n-The Council is scheduled to vote on July 21 whether to end or continue a contract with Flock Safety.\n- In their first year of use, police reported the devices aided 107 felony arrests and the recovery of 80 stolen vehicles collectively valued at nearly $1.3 million. (this has an average value of about $16,000 per car - WAY below the Costa Mesa value for new cars at $50,000 and used vehicles at $28,000 (this number was either underestimated or simply made up)\n- Police officials have used the camera data to track wives, girlfriends, family members (this is not a permitted use of the camera data) this clearly shows the systems vulnerabilities.\n\nDo the risks outweigh the benefits of this LPRs - please opine",
